observations.recommendation:
We recommended and Management agreed to:
Conduct the semestral physical count of inventories;
Prepare and submit the semestral RPCI to the AT;
Reconcile the result of the physical count with the accounting records; and
Immediately investigate if there is a discrepancy noted between the RPCI and the accounting records, thus, an adjustment may be made, if necessary.

We recommended and Management agreed that:
All regular purchases shall be coursed through the inventory account, except those purchased out of the petty cash fund, which shall be for immediate use;
The GSO or the property supply/officer shall consolidate weekly the RIS for which supplies and materials were issued using the SSMI and submit the SSMI together with the original copy of the RIS to the Chief Accountant;
The Municipal Accountant shall prepare the JEV based on the SSMI submitted by the GSO or property/supply officer to record in the appropriate expenditure accounts; and
Ensure the correctness of entries and the posting of transactions in the General Ledgers hence to present the correct amount in the financial statements.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Continue to issue demand letters compelling the AOs or employees to settle immediately in full their outstanding CAs, either by liquidation or through payment/refund;
Stop the granting of additional CA to employees with unsettled/unliquidated CA, especially those unliquidated CA other than for the payment of salaries and wages;
Ensure that all CAs are liquidated at year-end in compliance with COA Circular No. 97-002 (d); and
Comply strictly with the requirements of Section 89 of PD No. 1445, COA Circular No. 97-002, and all related rules and regulations pertaining to granting and liquidation of CAs.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to direct:
The MDRRMO to submit the LDRRMFIP to COA and the concerned departments of the LGU;
The MA to prepare and submit to the AT a detailed schedule of the TLs-LDRRMF account balance;
The MDRRMO, MA and MBO to conduct periodic reconciliation of their records to ensure the correctness of the reported amounts for the appropriation and utilization of the LDRRMF; and
The MA and MT to determine the composition of the additional cash available in the bank accounts for LDRRM for the proper appropriation and subsequent utilization thereof.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Require the BAC to exercise due diligence in the adoption of the mode of procurement for a particular project;
Consider the clustering of similar infrastructure projects with small ABC;
Submit to the AT the following documents of the contractors for the aforesaid projects, for verification:
Mayor’s/Business Permit;
PhilGEPS Registration Number;
PCAB License; and
Omnibus Sworn Statement;
Let the BAC, TWG and Secretariat attend the seminar on RA No. 12009 and its IRR;
Compel the MA to ensure that all the necessary documents are attached and authorized before payment and submission to the COA; and
Observe proper authorization of officials concerned before proceeding with the procurement process/payment.

We recommended that the LCE require the:
Municipal Human Resource Management Office (MHRMO) to submit a copy of the Minutes of Meeting directing the Department Heads to schedule employees to report for duty during the pandemic;
Department Heads to submit the schedule of employees required to work during the pandemic stating the dates and purpose of work as directed by the LCE;
Municipal Health Officer to submit the schedule of PHWs required to work during the pandemic as directed by the LCE;
Chief of Offices concerned to submit the Office Order authorizing named personnel to physically report for work in their assigned hospital/health facility, offices or work stations; the prescribed working hours and dates of actual attendance during ECQ; and
MA to closely verify the correctness of related payrolls, disbursements or liquidation reports to ensure validity of transactions.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendation that Management instruct the GFPS to:
Ensure proper monitoring of planned GAD PAPs and the full implementation and utilization of GPB;
Continue completing, updating and maintaining of GAD database of information necessary for proper gender-responsive planning, programming, policy formation and in addressing priority gender issues;
Identify GAD activities in regular programs with attributed GPB through the use of HGDG; and
Support the GAR with the required reports/documents and furnish the same to the AT to facilitate audit of GAD.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

Create an Inventory Committee, preferably composed of the Planning and Development Office, Engineering Office, Treasurer’s Office, Accountant’s Office and Assessor’s Office to conduct an inspection and inventory of all road networks.

The created inventory committee shall conduct a physical count/inventory of all the Municipal roads and reconcile it with the Municipal Road Map and determine the existence and condition of the road components of each road for proper measurement and valuation using the prescribed forms such as: i) Local Road and Bridge Inventory and Condition Survey; ii) Report of Local Road Network; and iii) Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Network;

Direct the Municipal Accounting Office (MAO) to exert best effort to gather all details and information needed to determine the cost of the road lot, road components and its depreciable life of each road network and reconcile it with the recorded cost in the Registry of Public Infrastructures (RPI) and existing ledgers.

Thereafter, prepare the necessary adjusting entries to correct the recognition of Public Infrastructure – Roads, Highways and Bridges in the GL to ensure that the accounting and reporting procedures laid down under COA Circular No. 2015-008 were fully complied by the concerned offices.  Also, the same procedures shall be undertaken for other public infrastructures accounts;

Direct the MAO and the Treasurer’s Office to strictly prepare and maintain all the prescribed reports under COA Circular No. 2015-008.


Direct the Planning and Development Office to maintain the information on the local road network of the Municipality, particularly, the plans and programs of the construction, repair and maintenance of local roads and the depreciable life of the road networks in coordination with the Engineering Office;

Direct the Engineering Office to enhance the existing Local Road Network map aligned to the requirement of a road map described under the Department of the Interior and Local Government (DILG) Memorandum Circular No. 2017-159 and Local Roads Assets Management Manual for Local Government Units (LGUs).

As the office that undertakes the construction and repair of the local roads, documents relative thereto shall be maintained so that the necessary and detailed information of a certain road project, such as complete description of the road and the cost segregation of the road components are available anytime when needed by the accounting and general services office and other stakeholders;

Direct the Assessor’s Office to prepare and maintain the tax maps, which are used as basis for identifying the ownership of all the road lots in the city road network and also assists in determining the cost of the road lots with no available costs.

We recommended that Management:

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to draw the necessary correcting entries for the negative and erroneous balances due for adjustments;


Issue demand letters to and negotiate with the remaining AOs who did not conform with the staggered salary deductions scheme on their preferred manner of payment without prejudice to the requirements of pertinent law, rules and regulations;

Require the DO to immediately refund all cash advances for payroll which remain unused or unreleased as of December 31, 2020.  Henceforth, all cash advances for payroll shall be fully liquidated or refunded as at year-end.


Devise other effective methods to increase the liquidation/payment rate and zero out outstanding cash advances;

Include the appropriate sanctions provided in the abovementioned rules and regulations in the demand letters sent to AOs. Strictly enforce the appropriate sanctions upon the inability of the AOs to liquidate their cash advance/s despite their receipt of the demand letter; and

Strictly comply with the requirements of Section 89 of Presidential Decree (PD) No. 1445, COA Circular No. 97-002, and all related rules and regulations pertaining to cash advances.

We recommended that Management:

Coordinate with the concerned LGUs/agencies as regards the terms and conditions of the unutilized grants;

Ensure that all grants or fund transfers, be it from National Government Agencies (NGAs), Government-Owned and Controlled Corporations (GOCCs) or LGUs shall have MOA in order to give basis in the utilization and reporting of necessary transactions relative to fund transfers and in order for the Audit Team to verify the terms and conditions and the timeline for the implementation of the fund transfers, the treatment of any unused balance upon completion of the purpose and the handling of unutilized/unexpended grants/fund transfers due to non-implementation of PPAs; 

Designate a focal person who would be coordinating and responsible in monitoring the status of project and/or programs implementation of funds transferred from SAs, be it from NGA, GOCC or LGU; and/or

Request for reclassification of these funds when necessary, if these funds had been expensed by the SAs in order to maximize the utilization of the funds and be used to implement relative programs thereto.

We recommended that Management instruct the GFPS to:

Continue the completion, updating and maintaining the GAD Database timely information necessary for proper gender-responsive planning, programming, policy formation and in addressing priority gender issues;

Identify GAD activities through the use of HGDG, update regularly the GAD Plan and identified projects to address the GAD issues and concerns in the Municipality;

Support the GAD AR with the required reports/documents and furnish the same to the Audit Team to facilitate audit of GAD fund utilization; and

Ensure proper monitoring of planned GAD PAPs and the full implementation of GPB.

