We recommended that Management:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to draw the necessary correcting entries for the negative and erroneous balances due for adjustments;
Issue demand letters to and negotiate with the remaining accountable officers who did not conform with the staggered salary deductions scheme on their preferred manner of payment without setting aside the requirements of pertinent law, rules and regulations;
Require the DO to immediately refund all cash advances for payroll which remain unused or unreleased as of December 31, 2019;
Implement immediately the directives of COA Circular No. 2012-004 against accountable officers with outstanding cash advances which were granted prior to CY 2011 and seriously consider the necessary sanctions on the failure to liquidate;
Devise other effective methods to increase the liquidation/payment rate and zero out outstanding cash advances; and
If warranted after review and evaluation, file request for authority to write-off dormant unliquidated cash advances to COA Office, duly supported with applicable documents and in accordance with the procedures prescribed in COA Circular No. 2016-005, and henceforth strictly adhere with the governing law, rules and regulations on the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advances.

To address these deficiencies, we recommended that the Municipal Accountant: 
If warranted after careful assessment, consider the request for write-off of the unidentified balance of ₱52,343 accounted as Prior Years Adjustment;

Effect correcting entries for the net amount of (₱54,000) erroneously included in the reports pertaining to unliquidated cash advances; and

Device monitoring scheme that would ensure that cash advances for local travels are liquidated within 30 days upon return of the LGU official or employee.
We also recommended that Management: 
Issue demand letters compelling the erring AOs to immediately settle in full their outstanding cash advances, either by liquidation, by payment or through salary deductions; 

Require the AOs to provide a definite period to which deductions shall be made against their salaries to fully pay their dues, the period of which must not exceed one year;

Consider utilizing the unclaimed terminal leave benefits of retired and separated accountable employees, if allowed, in the settlement of receivables;

Strictly discontinue the practice of granting special purpose cash advance to elected officials;

Ensure that no cash advance shall be allowed in favor of those who are not employees or officials of the LGU; and

Strictly comply with the requirements of Section 89 of PD 1445, COA Circular No. 97-002, and all related rules and regulations pertaining to cash advances.

We recommended that Management prepare and issue a well-defined set of policies and guidelines governing the implementation of AICS program which must be aligned with the guidelines issued by the DSWD governing the grants of AICS.  The policies and guidelines may contain the following:

Kind of financial assistance (burial, transportation, medical, educational, food, shelter and others);
Limitations on the amounts given per kind of financial assistance;
Criteria in granting the financial assistance and the documentary requirements for each particular case; and
Well defined roles and responsibilities of the officials processing requests.

We recommended that Management:
Follow-up incessantly the approval by the NSWMC of its 10-year SWM Plan to pave way and set direction in the effective implementation of the solid waste management program of the Municipality;
Encourage and provide needed assistance to the remaining 13 barangays to establish their own MRFs for the collection, segregation, recycling of biodegrable, recyclable, compostable and reusable wastes; 
Provide adequate assistance in restoring the five not functional barangay MRFs; and

Observe the standards and requirements for the collection, transport and handling of solid waste as required under Section 1(b) Rule X of the IRR of RA No. 9003 by providing the necessary training to the SWM staff and personnel to ensure that solid wastes are properly handled and that the risk of hazards to them and to the public are avoided or minimized.

We recommended that Local Chief Executive require:

the Municipal Accountant to justify the certification in processing of payment even in the absence requirements documents and in the future to strictly comply with Section 6 of COA Circular No. 2012-001;

require the concerned contractor to post warranty security and submit a copy of request for suspension;

the Municipal Engineer to comply and justify the noted deficiencies, and

the former BAC to comply and justify the aforementioned deficiencies and in the future, the current BAC to strictly comply with the provisions enumerated in RIRR of RA 9184.

